driver: Make add_sentinel a real inline functionPutting an inline function in a .c file does not do anything exceptnconfuse the compiler.  Newer versions of gcc will complain loudly aboutnthis, and refuse to build, so put the function in a .h file so that itncan actually be used as an inline function, making everyone happy.nnSigned-off-by: Greg Kroah-Hartman <gregkh@linuxfoundation.org>n

driver/ppm_types.h: delete the fileIt's not needed (kernel code isn't going to be built on othernplatforms), so just directly include <linux/types.h> in the .h filesninstead.nnSigned-off-by: Greg Kroah-Hartman <gregkh@linuxfoundation.org>n

driver: properly predefine variablesTwo variables were defined in ppm.h, but the .c files that declared themndid not include ppm.h, making sparse complain about these.  Properlyninclude the .h file, and move 2 structures that are only used in main.c,ninto main.c to avoid having to have a bunch of .h files in ppm.h thatnare not needed.nnSigned-off-by: Greg Kroah-Hartman <gregkh@linuxfoundation.org>n

fix error message so that it is reachable and matches other checks in kernel driver
No longer including unistd_32.h or unistd_64.h. The kernel knows what to doThe kernel knows its configuration, and will pick the correct unistd.hn
No longer assuming that syscall IDs start at 0This is a valid assumption for x86, but not for many other arches (per-EABI ARM,nMIPS, etc).n
presense of __NR_socketcall is now checked more directlyPreviously we were looking at __x86_64__ to see if we had that system call. NownI directly look at __NR_socketcall, which is more portablen
generic __x86_64__ -> CONFIG_X86_64

Checks for split 64-bit syscall arguments are more portableThis is described in syscall(2). Some syscalls take 64-bit arguments. Onnarches that have 64-bit registers, these arguments are shipped in a register.nOn 32-bit arches, however, these are split between two consecutive registers,nwith some alignment requirements. Some require an odd/even pair while somenothers require even/odd. For now I assume they all do what x86_32 does, andnwe can handle the rest when we port those.n

syscall table no longer checks for x86_64. Looks at the individual syscallsThere were some __x86_64__ checks whose purpose wasn't entirely clear. Mostly InTHINK they were meant to separate the syscalls that existed on eachnarchitecture, but this wasn't done perfectly: there were syscalls that existed,nbut were masked out by the #ifdef. This patch removes the check for x86_64, andnchecks each syscall for existence individually.nnIt may be a good idea to do this across the board for ALL the syscalls. The Cnpreprocessor can't quite do that I don't think, but we can generate the headernwe want.n

mmap() is allowed to have VM_EXECThe kernel driver was making sure that mmap( /dev/sysdig0 ) was gettingnuserspace memory with the (vma->vm_flags & VM_EXEC) flag clear. For whatevernreason this is not true on ARM: VM_EXEC is set there. I can't tell why yet, butnthings work fine after removing this check, and it seems benign enough.n

Added comment describing lack of alignment in preadv/pwritevpreadv/pwritev have a 64-bit 'offset' argument in userspace. The system call,nhowever, has two separate 32-bit arguments. This is different from syscalls likenpread where the syscall has a 64-bit argument.nnIn the latter case, alignment requirements apply. In the former (preadv) case,nhowever, NO alignment requirements apply, since as far as the kernel isnconcerned, there are no 64 bit arguments.nnTo be absolutely clear, here are the syscall definitions of preadv and preadn(I'm looking at fs/read_write.c in Linux 3.14):nnSYSCALL_DEFINE4(pread64, unsigned int, fd, char __user *, buf,ntttsize_t, count, loff_t, pos)nSYSCALL_DEFINE5(preadv, unsigned long, fd, const struct iovec __user *, vec,nttunsigned long, vlen, unsigned long, pos_l, unsigned long, pos_h)nnNote that pread64 has a single loff_t pos while preadv has a split pos.n

Once in a million years, args->arg_data_size becomes 0. When this happens and the argument being parsed is a string not coming from userspace, this causes the index dest[args->arg_data_size - 1] to 0xFFFFFFFF and causing a kernel panic.In this fix, we exit the callback with buffer full if arg_data_size is 0, and also replace strncpy with strlcpy, avoiding the need to call strlen again.n

Add `symlink(at)?` syscalls. Add `evt.abspath` filter field.This commit adds support for the following syscalls:nn- symlinkn- symlinkatnnIn addition to those syscalls a new set of filter fields was added:nn- evt.abspathn- evt.abspath.srcn- evt.abspath.dstnnThose field are only used for the syscall `symlinkat` but might benlater used for other `...at` syscalls as well (e.g. `renameat`,n`openat`, `linkat` and `unlinkat`). The purpose of the filter fieldsnis to aggregate the values of corresponding `dirfd` and `name`nparameters to form an absolute path.n

Start tracking session ids for threads.Start tracking session ids in threads and add the ability to filter onnsession ids in filter expressions.nnModify scap_threadinfo/sinsp_threadinfo to add a sid (session id)nmember. When filling in details on a process innscap_proc_fill_info_from_stats(), the session id is read from thencontents of /proc/<pid>/status, which was already being read--we justnneeded to fill in the value from the sscanf().nnThe sid is written and read along with other thread information in tracenfiles. This also bumps the block header version from V5 to V6. In placesnwhere the block header was checking for versions <= 5, they needed to benupdated to <= 6.nnA new filter expression proc.sid matches/displays the thread's sessionnid.nnOn a clone(), the session id is transferred to the new thread from thenparent. The same restrictions apply as the parent pid--if information onnthe parent process is not available for some reason, the session id willnnot be set.nnThe session id is not currently updated on a setsid() call. That will benhandled in the next commit.n

Add support for setsid events.Add support for setsid events, which allows for detailed information onnthe arguments/return value as well as parsing to update the session idnon a successful setsid call.nnAdd the new events PPME_SYSCALL_SETSID_{E,X} to event_table both for thendriver and libscap, and add the events to the syscall table fornsetsid. For exit events, the new session id is filled usingnPPM_AUTOFILL.nnIn libsinsp, on setsid exit events, when the return value isnsuccessful (>= 0) update the thread's session id m_sid to the returnnvalue of the setsid call.n
Add ability to filter on session leader name.Add proc.sname, which matches the current process's sesion leadernname. This is easy as the session id is the pid of the session's leader.n
Merge pull request #600 from draios/track-session-idsTrack session ids

Handle cases where the session leader has exited.When resovlving proc.sname, handle the case where the process withnpid=proc.sid has exited. I ran into this when using the pipe installernexample, where the top level bash installer spawns subshells which innturn run the python, etc processes we want to track.nnIn this case, walk the process ancestor heirarchy until the session idnchanges or you reach the top process. The top process having the samensession id is considered the process leader, and its comm is used fornproc.sname.n

Add regression tests for proc.sid/proc.sname.The actual new change is to add a second trace file sessions.scap whichnshows the results of calling setsid -w ls, with results scoped to thenshell where setsid is run. This handles all the cases of tracking ansession id/name for an existing process (the base shell), execingnsetsid -w ls, which changes the sid and sname, and waiting for the lsnto exit.nnIn order to add this new trace file, I needed to change how thenregression tests were run. The current regression tests assumed that forna given input trace file that there would be a corresponding baselinendirectory with the results of running that trace file with all the setsnof arguments in sysdig_trace_regression.sh. That didn't really handlenforward-looking cases like this, where I don't want to run old filesnwith new combinations of arguments and didn't want to use old argumentsnon the new trace file.nnFix this by changing sysdig_batch_parser to skip running sysdig with angiven set of arguments when the corresponding baseline directory doesn'tnexist. If the directory does exist but the individual baseline filendoesn't exist, skip that file.nnThis change has zip files baseline-add-session-tests.zip andntraces-add-session-tests.zip, which should work based on mynunderstanding of TRAVIS_BRANCH. After merging this branch to dev I'llnupdate the actual baseline.zip/traces.zip files, and give anyone workingnon an active branch to rebase.nnThis won't handle the case of the master branch, though. I need to checknto see if sysdig_trace_regression is run outside of travis.n

Add check for is an open for reading/writing.While working on measuring performance for falco, I found that one ofnthe rule bottlenecks was checking for an open for reading/open fornwriting. Add startswith as a string comparison operator. (#623)Currently, the only way to do a substring match is the 'contains'rnoperator. This is less than ideal when you specifically want to test thernbeginning of a string for the substring, as contains will traverse thernentire string and may return a match in the middle of the string.rnrnAdd a startswith operator that specifically tests for a substring matchrnat the beginning of the string.rnrnThere were a few places in non-string comparison operators where anyrnoperator not in the set of supported operators was assumed to bern'contains'. Replace this with checks for all operators includingrn'icontains', 'startswith' with appropriate error messages.

Multi string search (#624)* Whitespace diffs.rnrnBreaking whitespace diffs into standalone commit.rnrn* Implement in (...) as hash table lookups.rnrnCurrently, a filtering expression with x in (a, b c, ...) isrntransformed into x=a or x=b or x=c or .... This can be slow for veryrnlong sets of a, b, c, especially when x has to be extracted from thernevent over and over.rnrnReplace this with a set membership test using unordered_set forrnPT_CHARBUF types.rnrnIn filter.cpp, for CO_IN operators check the type of the operand. Ifrnit's PT_CHARBUF, loop over the items in the (a, b, c) set and callrnadd_filter_value() for each. Otherwise, the current behavior is kept.rnrnsinsp_filter_check::add_filter_value now saves pointers to the filterrnvalues in the unordered_set m_val_storages_members, containing pairsrnof (pointer, length). Note that these are only pointers--the actualrnvalues are still held in m_val_storages.rnrnIn sinsp_filter_check::flt_compare, for CO_IN operators simply check thernunordered_set and if a match is found return true. This used to be deadrncode given how all CO_INs were replaced with a sequence of x=a or x=b orrn..., but is used again.rnrnCustom functors g_hash_membuf/g_equal_to_membuf hash and compare thernpointer-to-datas. When compiling with gcc, this simply uses gnu'srnbuilt-in hash function for a pointer and length, which is quiternfast. Otherwise, a standalone function is used.rnrn* Take advantage of string length.rnrnTake advantage of string length when doing set membership tests:rnrn- When comparing strings in the hash equality function, only botherrn  doing the buffer comparison when the string lengths match.rnrn- It can be inefficient to hash a very long string when all members ofrn  the set are short strings. To make this case faster, keep track ofrn  the minumum and maximum string length across the set members andrn  only bother doing the set comparison of the lengths overlap.rnrnTo effectively use this, the length needs to be filled in whenrnsinsp_filter_check::flt_compare() is called, so do a pass over thernexisting filterchecks and actually return the actual string length whenrnit's easily known. In flt_compare(), if the type is a string and thernprovided length is 0, do a strlen() to find it. This should be very rarernnow that the length is properly passed back.rn

Dont sanitize strings filters (#625)* Switch back to erase/remove_if for sanitization.rnrnIt turns out that with -O3 (release flags), using erase/remove_if withrnan operator struct is slightly faster than the inline version that wasrnhere, as the compiler can inline the operators. It isn't faster with -O2rnand is much slower without optimization.rnrnOptimize for the release build by adding the operators back.rnrn* Whitespace diffs.rnrnMaking whitespace changes in separate commit.rnrn* Make sanitize_string cfgable and off for filters.rnrnModify sinsp_filter_check::extract to take an optional argumentrnsanitize_strings, defaulting to true. It controls whether thernfiltercheck should sanitize any string arguments when extracting thernvalue from the event.rnrnThe only place where it is set to false is inrnsinsp_filter_check::compare(). This means that when comparing eventsrnagainst a filter expression, any string values are not sanitized. Theyrnwill still be sanitized when the events are displayed.rnrnThis significantly speeds up users like falco that have complicatedrnfilter expressions that run against lots of events.rn

Allow multiple filters (#627)* Whitespace diffs.rnrnPutting whitespace changes in a separate commit.rnrn* Add optional support for multiple filters.rnrnAdd support for an additional set of individual filters that can runrnalongside the main filter set in sinsp::set_filter(). Each additionalrnfilter comes with a list of event types for which the filter should run.rnrnsinsp::add_evttype_filter adds an event type filter to the inspector. Itrnprovides a list of event types and a sinsp_filter pointer. The list ofrnevent types can be empty, implying the filter is a catchall filter andrnshould run for all event types. This does not replace the main functionrnset_filter()--the idea is that you can specify a global filter as wellrnas per-event type filters. Both will run for all events.rnrnAn array m_filter_by_evttype maps from event type to a list ofrnsinsp_filter pointers. Each list at index i holds the filters thatrnshould run for events with type i. A filter can run for multiple eventrntypes, so the sinsp_filter pointers can appear in multiple lists.rnrnThere's a separate list m_catchall_evttype_filters that contains filtersrnthat should run for all event types.rnrnThe individual filter pointers are also held in a list m_evttype_filtersrnso they can be cleaned up on close().rnrnA new method run_filters_on_evt() handles the details of running thernmain filter, catchall filters, and the individual filters. It finds thernfilters related to the event's type, and runs those filters.rnrnFalco uses the lua callbacks in lua_parser{_api} to populate filters asrnthe lua code parses the rule's condition, so also modify lua_parser tornadd a optional flag to get_parser that steals the m_filter object andrncreates a new one. Falco calls get_parser for each rule's condition,rnwhich allows it to create a sinsp_filter object for each rule.rn

Properly set length for extracted filenames. (#630)While merging together #624 (multi string search) and #625 (don'trnsanitize strings), the length was only being set when stringrnsanitization was enabled.rnrnAdditionally, the length was not being initialized to 0, meaning that itrnwas not defined.rnrnThis led to some FPs for some of the falco tests.
Initialize per-evttype filter array. (#631)Set the contents of the per-evttype filter array to NULL pointers sornonly those lists that are created while running are deleted.
Don't free lua state in lua_parser. (#632)The lua_state is being freed/closed on the falco side, so it shouldn'trnbe closed here.

Move eventtype filters into standalone class (#633)* Whitespace diffs.rnrnChecking in separate from other changes.rnrn* Move evttype filters into own class.rnrnThinking ahead to an embeddable falco, move evttype filters into its ownrnclass sinsp_evttype_filter. The inspector creates one of these objectsrnon demand whenever add_evttype_filter is called. Otherwise, from falco'srnview the interface hasn't changed.rn

Consider SERV sockets to also be ip sockets. (#636)Add SCAP_FD_IPV{4,6}_SERVSOCK to the socket types considered iprnsockets. The type can be set to SERVSOCK based on the port number afterrnother system calls.

Changes for falco-engine (#640)* Minor header file cleanups.rnrnRelated to changes in https://github.com/draios/falco/pull/103. Probablyrnbest to let that PR merge first.rnrn* Add abilty to disable filters.rnrnMost of the changes are to pass along a name with a filter when adding arnfilter via add(). This name can be used for a new methodrnsinsp_evttype_filter::enable(), which takes a pattern regex which isrnmatched against the names and a bool enabled flag.rnrnTo manage the new name and enabled state along with the filter, wrap thernexisting sinsp_filter object in a wrapper filter_wrapper containing thernsinsp_filter, enabled flag, and name. Flag bind events with EF_MODIFIES_STATE. (#635)Flag bind enter and exit events with EF_MODIFIES_STATE.rnrnbind exit events need the flag because they can change the type ofrnm_fdinfo from SCAP_FD_IPV{4,6}_SOCK to _SERVSOCK based on the portrnnumber.rnrnbind enter events need the flag because if filters run and don't matchrnon the enter event, it clears the thread's m_lastevent_type, whichrnprevents the exit event from getting a handle to the m_fdinfo.

Support glob matching on strings. (#653)* Whitespace diffs.rnrnCommitting separate from other changes.rnrn* Fix windows build.rnrnWindows has min()/max() macros that conflict with thernfunctions from numeric_limits::min()/max(), so disable them via #definernNOMINMAX.rnrn* Support glob matching on strings.rnrnAdd new comparison glob that allows for glob matching onrnpathnames. The glob matching is handled by a utils function glob_matchrnthat calls fnmatch on windows and PathMatchSpec on windows.rnrnThis handles simple stuff like *, ?, etc. but not shell specificrnextensions.rn

Addl docker container info (#655)* Whitespace changes.rnrnChecking in separate from other changes.rnrn* Change glob matching to allow path separators.rnrnChange glob matching to allow *, ? to match the path separatorrn/. This allows for matching /proc/* as anything starting with /procrninstead of having to match all path components.rnrn* Add ability to detect/show privileged status.rnrnIn sinsp_container_manager::parse_docker(), parse the Privileged fieldrnout of the json output and use it to set the instance variablernm_privileged.rnrnModify container_to_json/parse_container_json_evt to dump/read thernprivileged status from .scap files.rnrnNew filtercheck container.privileged returns the privileged statusrnas a boolean.rnrnAlthough other container types support the notion of privileged, I onlyrnsupport this filtercheck for docker containers. For non-dockerrncontainers, container.privileged returns NULL.rnrnWrite privileged to/from scap files.rnrn* Add ability to display container mount info.rnrnIn sinsp_container_manager::parse_docker(), parse the Mounts field intorna vector of class container_mount_info objects.rnrnModify container_to_json/parse_container_json_evt to dump/read thernmount information from .scap files.rnrnNew filtercheck container.mounts displays the mount information as arncomma-separated list of mount tuplesrn<source>:<dest>:<mode>:<rdwr>:<propagation>, for example:rnrnmounts=/tmp:/foo/tmp::true::,/var/lib/docker/volumes/51c63c9efcd052551dd4898736dffb2692acbf6afd8d3f4d2f0cb89a7f8ace4a/_data:/data::true:rprivate:rnrnNote how empty values for mode/propagation turn into empty strings.rnrnThis output is pretty awkward and verbose, so there are additionalrnfilterchecks that allow you to select any given attribute from arnsingle mount. New filterchecksrncontainer.mount.{source,dest,dest,mode,rdwr,propagation} allow selectingrnany of the mount information indexed either by mount idrncontainer.mount.mode[0] or mount sourcerncontainer.mount.mode[/var/log]. container.mount.source is different inrnthat it's indexed by the mount destination instead of the mount source.rnrnWhen selecting a mount by source/dest pathname, you can provide a globrnmatch instead (e.g. container.mount.mode[/var/log/*]). In this case, thernfirst matching mount is returned.rnrnYou can also use this indexing to return all the mount information for arnsingle mount. New filtercheck container.mount returns the tuplerninformation for a single mount, indexed by number (container.mount[0])rnor source path/glob (container.mount[/var/log]. This can also be used torntest if a mount exists, like container.mount[/proc/*] to detectrncontainers that mount /proc or other sensitive directories.rnrnWrite mounts to/from .scap files.rn

use vmalloc instead of kmalloc to allocate the PPM_IOCTL_GET_PROCLIST sotrage. Even if the required amount of memory is typically small, there's no need to use kmalloc since we don't need contiguous pages. vmalloc will have lower probability of failing.

Path prefix search (#660)* Add ability to test a path against many prefixesrnrnAdd a data structure that allows testing a path aka /var/log/messagesrnagainst a set of path prefixes (/usr, /bin, /var/log, ...).rnrnThinking ahead to use in libsinsp, the search structure uses pointer +rnlength pairs instead of strings, meaning that it does not copy any data,rnonly refers to it. This way the structure doesn't copy filtercheckrnvalues.rnrnIn order to share the idea of a pair of pointer + length between thisrnstructure and the unordered_set used by in (...) set membership tests,rnmove the hashing and equality function from filterchecks to a standalonernheader filter_value.h and use it for the unordered_map.rnrnThe paths are held in a tree-like structure. At each level, an unorderedrnmap has the path components for that level and a sub-tree of paths forrnthat root.rnrnThe tree can change if new search paths are prefixes of any of therncurrent paths (the sub-tree for the longer path is replaced by thernprefix). If a new search path is a suffix of any existing path no changernis made, as it is already covered by the prefix.rnrnMatching involves splitting off the first directory component andrntesting it against the values at that level. If a match is found, itrnrecursively calls match for the subtree.rnrn* Add pmatch operator, using prefix_search struct.rnrnRemove the definitions of filter_value_member_t/hash function/equalityrnfunction from filterchecks.h, renaming it to filter_value_t along thernway.rnrnAdd an operator CO_PMATCH/pmatch which takes a set of values likernCO_IN does, but requires that the left hand side of the comparison is arnPT_CHARBUF. When filter values are added, they are added to the newrnpath_prefix_search object m_val_storages_paths.rnrnin ::flt_compare, when the operator is CO_PMATCH, test the value againstrnm_val_storages_paths.rnrnAs a result, you can run sysdig using a command line like:rnrnsudo ./userspace/sysdig/sysdig evt.type=open and fd.directoryrnpmatch (/var, /usr)rnrnand see all the file opens for files below either /var or /usr.rn

Detect/remove stale threadinfo in clone childrenWhen parsing clone exit events, specifically for the child half of anclone and when in a container, detect and potentially remove stalenthreadinfo state for the child thread.nnGenerally the client have of a clone is responsible for creating thenthread state for the new thread, as long as the parent is in ancontainer. See the parent half of the if(childtid == 0) statement. Wensimply need to verify in the child half that the parent really was in ancontainer.nnYou can find the parent thread id from the syscall return information,nwhich is moved up from below. Look up the parent thread and see if itsnvtid/vpid differs from tid/pid. If so, any existing thread state must benstale and remove it. Note that you can't usenevt->m_tinfo->get_parent_thread() directly, as that comes from thenexisting potentially stale threadinfo.nnThis fixes https://github.com/draios/sysdig/issues/664.n

Expose mesos token (#701)* Whitespace diffs.rnrnCommitting separate from other changes.rnrn* Split mesos auth into standalone classrnrnSplit mesos auth into a standalone class so you can get anrnauthentication token without doing any of the other mesos-relatedrnactivities.rnrnThe auth work is now in mesos_auth.cpp and has the authenticate() andrnrefresh_token() methods that used to be in mesos.cpp and a new methodrnget_token() that returns the token.rnrnmesos.cpp had an unused bool m_token_authentication which was removedrnand not carried over.rnrn* Manage periodic refresh of tokens.rnrnmesos_auth's refresh_token() method is now responsible for deciding whenrnto regenerate a token. It maintains its own time at which a token wasrnlast generated and also only generates one when dcos_enterpriserncredentials were provided.rnrnauthenticate() now becomes private so it can only be called from thernmesos_auth class itself. refresh_token() is the main interface to updaternthe token.rnrnget_token() will always call refresh_token(), so callers only usingrnget_token() can be sure that the token is refreshed automatically. Theyrncan also force a token refresh via refresh_token().rnrn* Add ability to change auth hostname from localhostrnrnOn the mesos slaves, you can't get an auth token fromrnlocalhost. Instead, you need another hostname like master.mesos.rnrnSo add the ability to override the hostname in the constructor.rnrn* Expose the list of marathon uri tokens.rnrnThis is needed by the analyzer to update an app check's config with thernright uri.rn

Add support for tagging falco rules. (#746)Add support for tagging falco rules with tags, enabling/disabling setsrnof rules based on the tags they have, and having the ability to run arnsubset of loaded rules against a given event:rnrn - in sinsp_evttype_filter::add(), you now provide a set of tags forrn   each filter (can be empty).rn - internal to sinsp_evttype_filter, m_filter_by_tag maintains a mappingrn   from tag to list of filters having that tag. This is used forrn   sinsp_evttype_filter::enable_tags, which allows enabling/disablingrn   all filters having a given tag.rn - In sinsp_evttype_filter, rules are grouped into rulesets. All rules havern   a ruleset of 0 which reflects their original loaded status.rn - In ::enable/::enable_tags(), you can provide an optional rulesetrn   id (number, defaults to 0) that lets you select sets of rules thatrn   are enabled given that ruleset id.rn - The filter_wrapper boolean is now a vector indexed by rulesetrn   id. filter_wrapper is also now a class with a constructor thatrn   initializes the vector to one ruleset id (0) that is enabled.rnrnHaving multiple rulesets lets you call enable/enable_tags multiple timesrnwith different rulesets. It's one set of rules, but the ruleset allowsrnyou to have different subsets of rules enabled/disabled.rnrn - ::run() also takes an optional ruleset argument. Once you find thern   matching set of filters given the event type, check the filter's enabledrn   vector to see if the filter is enabled given the provided ruleset. Ifrn   so, the filter runs against the event.rn - In sinsp_evttype_filter, clean up use of auto loops to use const referencesrn   whenever possible and use std:: for stl objects in the header file.

Detect aname loops (#753)* Whitespace diffs.rnrnChecking in separate from other changes.rnrn* Combine parent state traversal w/ loop detectionrnrnReplace the ad-hoc parent thread state traversal that was in severalrnfilterchecks as well as in the mesos/coreos code with a central way torntraverse parent thread state and detect potential loops at the samerntime. A new method traverse_parent_state traverses the parent state fromrnthe current thead and takes a function that is called for each threadrnwhile traversing.rnrnThis prevents infinite loops like observed inrnhttps://github.com/draios/falco/issues/208.rnrnThis doesn't address the underlying cause of what caused the threadrnstate to get corrupted in the first place. That's tracked by a separaternissue https://github.com/draios/sysdig/issues/752.rnrnIn the 4 filterchecks that used to traverse parent state (proc.sname,rnproc.loginshellid, proc.aname, proc.apid), replace the direct traversalrnwith a call to traverse_parent_state + an appropriate visitorrnfunction.rnrnUpdate mesos's get_env_mesos_task_id, which used to do a combination ofrnrecursion and get_parent_task_id to traverse parent state, with a visitorrnand traverse_parent_state. It stops as soon as any of the environmentrnvariables for a thread are found.rnrnThis version doesn't explicitly skip pid 1, but I don't think that wasrnstrictly necessary as init wouldn't have those environment variablesrnanyway.rnrnAlso replace a similar process in coreos to find rkt pods.rnrn* Add regression tests for parent state loopsrnrnAdd a new trace file parent_state_loop.scap to the traces zip that has arnseries of processes with malformed parent state containing a loop.rnrnAdd 3 new sysdig command lines that test filterchecks/outputs that arernknown to traverse parent thread state.rnrnAlthough they should *not* cause an infinite loop, add a timeout to thernsysdig command line just to make sure it is terminated somewhat quickly.rn

(#789)* Start building standalone falco kernel modules.rnrnhttps://github.com/draios/falco/issues/215 pointed out a problem withrncompatibility between latest sysdig kernel module and falco 0.5.0. It wasrnalready building its own driver, but the remaining changes are to changernthe device name from sysdig to falco, module falco-probe, etc.rnrnThese changes will allow for automatically building the falco-probernkernel module on a variety of kernel platforms and runningrnsysdig-probe-loader (under the name falco-probe-loader) to get a modulernas needed.rnrnWhile doing this, merge the nearly identicalrnbuild_{falco,sysdig,sysdigcloud} functions into build_probe. Handle netlink sockets (#809)* Minimal support for NETLINK sockets.rnrnAdd minimal support for AF_NETLINK sockets, with the new typernSCAP_FD_NETLINK. This is mostly done so they are not mixed up withrnSCAP_FD_UNKNOWN sockets, which are not expected to be in scap files atrnall.rnrnThe type is used when first parsing a fd from its fd num/domain num inrnsinsp_parser::add_socket or when parsing /proc/net/netlink inrnscap_fd_read_netlink_sockets_from_proc_fs(). After that, the type isrncopied when converting from scap_fdinfos to sinsp_fdinfos inrnsinsp_threadinfo::add_fd_from_scap.rnrnThere is limited support for displaying information on netlink fds. Therntypechar is 'n', the typestring is netlink/<NETLINK>, and they don'trnhave any additional information or a category for them.rnrn* Improve handling of potentially unknown fds.rnrnEnsure we better handle fds that can't be mapped to a specificrnscap_fd_type.rnrnWhen reading a descriptor from a scap file, ignore SCAP_FD_UNKNOWNrnsockets and don't return an error. When writing a descriptor to a scaprnfile, skip SCAP_FD_UNKNOWN descriptors.rnrnWhen parsing a socket fd, if we don't map a type log an error but continue.rn

Adding ability to open trace files from fds (#838)* Adding ability to open trace files from fdsrnrnAdd the ability to open scap files or inspectors from a fd. Makes itrnpossible to open other objects that return a fd and treat those objectsrnas if they were a file.rnrn - Add new functions scap_open_offline_fd, scap_dump_open_fd that takern   all the same arguments as their filename versions but take a fdrn   instead of a filename. scap_open_offline_int now takes a gzfile whichrn   has been opened by one of the top-level functions.rn - scap_open's args struct now contains a fd. If non-zero, it takesrn   precedence over filename and the fd is used to open a gzfile viarn   gzdopen().rn - New function scap_event_reset_count sets the read event count torn   0. Used when rewinding a scap file to start over.rn - Add some more useful error messages torn   scap_read_{proclist,userlist,fdlist} when reading more than expected.rn - also add fdopen variants to sinsp_dumper/sinsp. They call thern   appropriate scap fd variants. most of sinsp::open moves to sinsp::open_int().rn - Add is_open() and written_events() methods to sinsp_dumper(). Usefulrn   when writing files via fd to track progress.rn - In sinsp::init(), after rewinding the file also reset the eventrn   count.rn - Add a sinsp::fseek() which just uses scap_fseek().rnrn* Add ftell/ability to read bytes written.rnrnAdd scap_dump_ftell, which maps to gztell, andrnsinsp_dumper::next_write_position, which uses scap_dump_ftell.rnrn* Add ability to skip proc scan for fd opens.rnrnAdd an argument to scap_dump_open_fd that controls whether or not to dorna scan of /proc when initializing the dump file.rnrnIn sinsp_dumper::fdopen, set this to false. Also write the thread tablernto the file, following recent changes to sinsp_dumper::open.rn

Set close-on-exec flag for driver fds. (#851)While debugging some agent unit tests, I noticed that after a fork +rnexec the number of driver references was higher than expected. Some ofrnthese problems can be fixed within the tests, but it's also useful tornset the close-on-exec flag for the driver fd so it's closed during anrnexec.rnrnAlso fix some error messages that were referring to a hardcodedrnsysdig_probe instead of PROBE_DEVICE_NAME.

Perf scaling for excessive close() events (#852)* Drop close() exit events with error returnsrnrnFor the agent, we don't need to process close() events where an errorrnoccurred because they won't affect our fd tracking. Drop these eventsrnearly so we don't take a perf hit from superfluous but valid close() calls.rnrn* Drop close() events earlyrnrnThis avoids locking the consumer(s) and a getnstimeofday() callrnrn* Drop close() enter eventsrnrnIf the close fd is invalid or not open, drop the enter event becausernit will have no side effects on the agent.rnrn* code cleanuprnrn* Restrict close() drop logic to the agent + code cleanuprnrn* Add support for kernels older than 3.4.xrnrn* Address review commentsrnrn* Don't process close() events with negative fdrnrn* Handle negative fd values correctlyrn

Overwrite ptid during execve (#914)In some scenarios we are missing many clone() events, but not the relative execve() (in the process of troubleshooting the cause of this).rnrnIn those cases, whenever the first event for the newly created process happens, sysdig will create a new fake <NA> process that doesn't have most fields set. Whenever the execve happens, some of these fields will be set (args, comm, container_id, ...), however the ptid remains to the default `-1`, meaning that parent navigation will not work.rnrnFrom the point of view of sinsp, this process will then appear as being inside a container but detached from the main process hierarchy, and this creates some issues on the Monitor/Secure side of things.

Squashed commit of the following:commit dac9260ff456a7d450f4d9f0a7b7d54bd5589834nAuthor: Mattia Pagnozzi <mattia.pagnozzi@gmail.com>nDate:   Thu Aug 3 20:51:14 2017 +0200nnAdd on_remove_container callbacknncommit b8884423f34f73448a7294b77b370be75261c141nAuthor: Luca Marturana <luca@sysdig.com>nDate:   Thu Jul 27 14:04:26 2017 +0200nnEvent only support for k8sn

Containers networking fixes (#922)* Add support for mapped container network modernrn* Fix wrong IP comparison within fd network filtersrnrn* minor changesrnrn* container_to_json should use htonl when dealing with m_container_iprn

Return container meta events. (#912)* Return container meta events.rnrnPreviously, container/k8s/mesos meta events, which included informationrnabout a newly created container/k8s/mesos entity, were dumped directlyrnto capture files but not returned in sinsp::next().rnrnThis causes problems if you're using a sinsp_dumper outside of therninspector and want to dump events to a file yourself.rnrnTo fix this, add a new inspector option set_internal_events_mode whichrncontrols whether or not internal events (i.e. container, k8s, mesos) arernreturned in live mode.rnrnIn the sysdig program, the -D option also enables internal events mode.rnrnAlso ensure that container meta events are returned/written before thernevent that creates the container. This involves saving the current scaprnevent to m_meta_skipped_evt when a meta event is created as arnside-effect of sinsp_parser::process_event(), and returning that eventrnthe next time sinsp::next() is called. With this change, there isn't anyrnneed for special handling of container events when dumping, so removernthat code.rnrn* Don't use unrelated m_meta_evt for k8s/mesos evtsrnrnWhen creating k8s/mesos events, it used to use m_meta_evt, which was arnnot-really-related event that happened to be the last container metarnevent that was created. There isn't any guarantee that that event hasrnanything to do with the k8s/mesos event being created, or is even valid.rnrnThis all happened to work because the only thing being used fromrnm_meta_evt was the thread id, which is always 0 (seernhttps://github.com/draios/sysdig/blob/dev/userspace/libsinsp/container.cpp#L538rnandrnhttps://github.com/draios/sysdig/blob/dev/userspace/libsinsp/container.cpp#L588).rnrnSo directly just set the thread id of the k8s/mesos event to 0 and getrnrid of the connection.rnrn* Get rid of unused m_skipped_evt.rnrnm_skipped_evt is not actually used, and might be confused withrnm_meta_skipped_evt, which is a system event like execve, clone, etc. isrndelayed when a container is created and emitted/written before thernsystem event.rnrnGet rid of m_skipped_evt and the unused method add_meta_event_and_repeatrnwhich used it.rnrn* Make notification events internal.rnrnThis allows them to be treated identically to other internal events inrncapture files.rn

Fix more valgrind errs (#938)* Initialize exepath to empty string.rnrnWhen converting a sinsp_threadinfo to a scap_threadinfo, make surernexepath is initialized.rnrnThis change was originally inrnhttps://github.com/draios/sysdig/pull/845/files, but got dropped duringrna conflict merge. This adds the change back.rnrn* Add scap_threadinfo ctor and use it vs ad-hoc initrnrnValgrind was reporting memory leaks when reading/writing trace files,rnand the leak was the table scap_threadinfo::scap_fdinfo as used byrnsinsp_thread_manager::dump_threads_to_file().rnrnThis function was re-using the same scap_threadinfo struct for allrnprocesses. The individual fds were being cleaned up, as they were in thernvector fdinfos_to_free, but not the hash table that contained them.rnrnFix this by reorganizing dump_threads_to_file a bit to not reuse arnscap_threadinfo struct across all the processes, but to use individuallyrncreated ones for each process, using scap_proc_free() to destroy thernscap_threadinfo struct.rnrnThere was no corresponding constructor, so add one that takes care ofrnthe malloc/memset as well as setting handle->m_lasterr when the mallocrnfails. Use that in dump_threads_to_file as well as inrnscap_proc_add_from_proc().rnrn* Add ability to set dumper's inspector.rnrnThis is used in other products that keep a sinsp_dumper around withrndifferent inspectors.rnrn* Allow proc info to be MAX_*_SIZE in lengthrnrnOne of the changes in https://github.com/draios/sysdig/pull/845 was tornrefuse to read process information that was exactly SCAP_MAX_*_SIZErncharacters in length, to make sure that the resulting string fit in arnbuffer of size SCAP_MAX_*_SIZE, including the trailing null.rnrnThis caused a problem when the trace file contained a processrninformation string that is exactly SCAP_MAX_*_SIZE characters long,rnwhich is actually allowed in the trace file.rnrnThe fix is to increase the buffer size by 1 and read up tornSCAP_MAX_*_SIZE characters, followed by setting array[size] to '0'.rn

Add ability to store values with search paths (#1007)Previously, path_prefix_search was a set membership test. You could testrna path P against a set of search paths S, and see if any Si was a prefixrnof P.rnrnExtend that to also store values along with each search path Si, makingrnit a map path_prefix_map instead of a set. This is done by templatingrnthe class with a Value v and storing the value at each leaf node in therntree. When searching, when you find a leaf node a pointer to itsrnassociated value is returned.rnrnpath_prefix_search remains as an instantiation of the templated map withrndummy values.

Fix AT_FDCWD 32-bit syscall decodingAT_FDCWD is equal to -100. In the 64-bit version of the syscall, itsnvalue as unsigned long is 18446744073709551516 (1<<64 - 100). However,nwhen the 32-bit syscall version is used, the value is truncated to 32nbits and AT_FDCWD is passed as 4294967196 (1<<32 - 100).nnCast the value to int to drop the high 32 bits (the dirfd argument isndefined to be an int anyway) and then compare the signed 32-bit values.n

Allow in operator to work with non-string values (#1049)When used by falco, an expression like xxx in (a, b, c) is stored withrnan operator CO_IN and the values a, b, c, etc as values added via callsrnto add_filter_value. (In sysdig, it's a bit more nuanced, with therntreatment dependent on what the type of xxx is).rnrnWhen checking, a the values a, b, c are stored in a set and a setrnmembership test tells you if a given test value matches one of a, b, c.rnrnFor non-string values, The values a, b, c, etc are parsed into rawrnvalues, converting things like numeric strings to 16 bit values, booleansrnto 0/1, etc.rnrnThis had a bug, though, as the value being stored in the set has itsrnlength set to the length of the original value (e.g. the stringrnrepresenting the port), and not the parsed raw value (2 bytes).rnrnThis fixes that bug by storing the parsed raw length instead of the unparsedrnlength. In turn, that required some other changes to return the parsedrnlength from functions like sinsp_filter_check::parse_filter_value andrnsinsp_filter_value_parser::string_to_rawval.

Allow sendto/recvfrom events for falco, add fd.name_changed filtercheck (#1052)* Allow sendto/recvfrom, msg events for falco.rnrnWe'll be using this to expand coverage for udp traffic, some of whichrncan be sent using sendto/recvfrom/sendmsg/recvmsg.rnrn* Add a filtercheck for when a fd name changesrnrnAdd a filtercheck fd.name_changed which is true when parsing an eventrnchanges the name of a fd. This mostly occurs when arnbind/connect/sendto/recvfrom/etc changes the ip/port informationrnassociated with a socket fd, and is useful if you want to track when arnstream of sendto/recvfroms on a single socket changes addresses.rnrnThis is done by adding a m_oldname to fdinfo, which is set whenrnthreadinfo returns a fd and associates it with an event. If afterrnparsing, the name changes, the filtercheck will return true.rnrnWhether the name changed or not is an event property and set at the endrnof sinsp_parser::process_event(). It does this by checking the originalrnfd name and comparing it to the fd name that exists after parsing thernevent.rn

Allow capture files with versions < software (#1084)The test between capture file version and software version was doing arnstrict comparison--the capture would only be read if the two versionsrnwere equal. This prevents newer versions of sysdig from reading olderrncapture files.rnrnTo fix this, change the test to only refuse to read a capture if itsrnmajor number is greater or major numbers are the same but minor numberrnis greater.

Fix pgid ns (#1080)* Rename pgid to vpgid to reflect it's in-namespacernrnhttps://github.com/draios/sysdig/pull/1044 added tracking of a process'srnprocess group id (pgid). However, this change didn't compeltely handlernprocess group ids in a namespace. When reading process information fromrn/proc, it was using the process group id from the global namespace. Whenrntracking execve()s and setpgid()s it would take the pgid from thernnamespace of the calling process.rnrnTo fix this, define the pgid to be the pgid from its current pidrnnamespace. And to make this clear, rename it to vpgid everywhere.rnrnThis commit handles renaming the variable at the scap/sinsprnlevels. Other changes will fix setpgid() handling to handle cases whenrnit's called in a pid namespace.rnrn* Rename the proc.pgid filtercheck to proc.vpgidrnrnThis reflects its real meaning (from the namespace)rnrn* Removing event parsing for setpgidrnrnThis means that if a setpgid occurs, the pgid of the process won't bernin-sync again until the next execve(), where the process's pgid isrnreturned by the driver in the exit event. However, we expect that thisrnwill cover most cases, and is dramatically simpler.rnrn* Fix logic for setting vpgidrnrnComment was right, but test was backwards.rn

Enable SME on userspace mappings (#1096)When AMD Secure Memory Encryption is enabled, kernel memory isrnencrypted. When we map the ring buffer into userspace, we must mark itrnencrypted as well, otherwise corruption occurs both in the ring inforn(userspace writes unencrypted ->tail, then kernel reads the encryptedrnvalue and trips up on ASSERTs in record_event_consumer) and the bufferrnitself (userspace treats encrypted event data as plaintext leading tornbogus lengths and eventually stack overflows by massive amounts).

Fix in netmasks (#1091)* Only do set equality/group searches for some typesrnrnPreviously, if an expression had an xxx in (a, b, c, ...) check, thernvalues a, b, c would be put in a set and xxx would do a set membershiprntest to see if it's in the set.rnrnFor almost all filtercheck types, this is preferred, but for some typesrnlike PT_IPV4NET, you can't actually do set membership tests, as thernnotion of equals isn't a simple == operator.rnrnSo for PT_IPV4NET and any type that trivially returns false fromrn::flt_compare(), instead of doing the set membership test, compare thernfiltercheck values individually and return true as soon as you find onernthat is equal.rnrnThis fixes https://github.com/draios/falco/issues/339.rnrn* Allow in matches for fd.netrnrnIf a filter check has an in operator against a set of values, which getsrnturned into a piecewise equality comparison, treat the operator CO_INrnjust like CO_EQ.rn

Allow fd.port to be used with in. (#1101)When the filtercheck is fd.port, it's handled byrnsinsp_filter_check_fd::compare_port, which checks both the source andrndestination port. This didn't accept an operator of CO_IN.rnrnChange this to do flt_compare() using the source and destination port,rnwhichh in turn uses set membership tests.

Allow evttype filters to work with syscalls (#1100)* Allow evttype filters to work with syscallsrnrnSyscalls have their own numbers but they weren't really handled byrnsinsp_evttype_filter. This meant that there wasn't a way to handlernfilters with evt.type=xxx clauses where xxx was a value that didn't haverna corresponding event entry (like madvise, for examples), or where arnsyscall like open could also be done indirectly via syscall(__NR_open,rn...).rnrnThis fixes that by also tracking the syscall numbers for an event likernopen or madvise. They are passed to add() as a separate set andrnthere are corresponding arrays/lists that map from a syscall number to arnlist of filters to run related to that syscall.rnrnin ::run(), if the event number if PPME_GENERIC_E/X, look at thernargument to find the syscall number and index into the syscall-specificrnvectors to find the right filters.rnrn* Move filters assignment to own branch.rnrnMakes it more clear about when it's set based on evttype vs syscall.rn

Preserve order between catchall & other filters (#1103)Previously, catchall filters were always matched against an event first,rnfollowed by any filters specificially linked to that event's type. Thisrndidn't preserve the order of filters as they appeared in the file,rnthough.rnrnInstead, assign a filter order for each filter and walk the catchall andrnevttype-specific filters in order, trying to match each against thernevent.rnrnThis fixes https://github.com/draios/falco/issues/354.

More ef drop falco (#1105)* Syncing driver and libscap event tables.rnrnCompare the driver and libscap event tables and fix any differences:rnrn - Some earlier unlink/unlinkat syscalls were missing the EF_OLD_VERSIONrn   flag.rn - Infrastructure events have an EC_INTERNAL flag.rnrn* Start skipping more syscalls at falco levelrnrnAdd an additional set of syscalls to be skipped by falco. Summarized,rnthese are:rnrn - getsock*, getpeer*: fetching info on socketsrn - getcwd: getting current directoryrn - pread,pwrite: reading from fds, so should be skipped like read/writern - get,setrlimit: changing process resources. Yes, set is a change, butrn   it's only for the current process and not other processes.rn - splice: copying from one fd to another, so skipped like read/writern - get*uid*: getting user information. Note that set*uid is stillrn   considered.rn - signaldeliver: noting that a process has been signaledrn - sem*: semaphore operationsrn - access: file access, so should be skipped like stat, etc.rnrn* Change EF_DROP_FALCO flag for additional syscallsrnrnAdd an additional set of syscalls to be skipped by falco. Summarized,rnthese are:rnrn - time/alarm/times/nanosleep: reading current timern - brk: changing process memory usagern - get*pid/pgrp/pgid/sid/tid/uid/gid/capget: getting process user/grouprn   informationrn - access/ustat/newfstatat: reading file informationrn - umask: changing default file mask. All opens are still considered.rn - setrlimit/getrusage/{u}getrlimit: getting resource usage and changing memory usagern   for current process.rn - getpriority/getscheduler/sched_get...: get current schedulingrn   priority. set... is still considered.rn - uname/getcpu/olduname: get kernel inforn - fsync/fdatasync: sync file to storagern - mprotect/madvise/mlock/munlock{all}/mremap/mincore: protect/control memory areasrn - rt_sig*/pause/signalfd*/eventfd*/sigprocmask/sigpending: signal/event handlingrn - getcwd: current working directoryrn - get/listxattr: reading file attributes. set is still considered.rn - io_*: async io controlsrn - exit_group: exiting a processrn - remap_file_pages: file mappingrn - mq_*: message queue handlingrn - waitid/waitpid: waiting on other processrn - get_robust_list: robust futex handling. set is still consideredrn - vmsplice: like splicern - getsock*/peer*: getting info on socketsrn - sem*/msg*: semaphore/message queue operations. Creating messagern   queues is still consideredrn - newselect: should be skipped like select/poll/etc.rnrnAlso *remove* the EF_DROP_FALCO flag forrn - sendto/recvfrom/sendmsg/recvmsg: these were previously changed torn   allowedrnrn* Add falco_consider to centralize flag comparisonsrnrnIn a few places we look at event flags to consider whether or not torninclude an event. Centralize this in a methodrnsinsp_evt::falco_consider() which in turn uses static methodsrnfalco_consider_{evtnum,syscallid}.rnrnThe flags that will result in a skipped event are any of:rn - EF_SKIPPARSERESETrn - EF_UNUSEDrn - EF_OLD_VERSIONrn - EF_DROP_FALCOrn

Check rulesets first (#1126)* Reorganize ruleset mgmt in sinsp_evttype_filterrnrnChange how rulesets are organized in sinsp_evttype_filter. Previouslyrnthe primary index into the set of filters was by event type. For filtersrnmatching an event type, each would be considered to see if they werernrelevant for a given ruleset, and if so, the filter would be run.rnrnThis ends up being inefficient for the use case of iterating overrnrulesets, as you end up traversing the list of filters for a given eventrntype N times for N rulesets.rnrnInstead, add a new object ruleset_filters which holds the set of filtersrnfor a given ruleset. The lists of filters indexed by evttype/syscallrnid move from the main object to the ruleset_filters object.rnrnAlso, get rid of the notion of catchall filters. If a filter reallyrnshould apply for all evttypes/syscalls, it just gets included in everyrnm_filter_by_{evttype,syscall} list. Catchall filters are highlyrndiscouraged and don't exist for the default falco ruleset, so it's ok tornnot have a special case for it. This ends up significantly simplifyingrn::run(), as you can iterate over a single list instead of two and don'trnneed to keep track of any order value for a given filter.rnrn* Fix memory leak.rnrnWhile running some tests using valgrind, I noticed that a value from arnnode that was removed due to a shorter path matching a value wasn'trnbeing deleted.rnrn* Properly remove filters on enable=falsernrnPreviously, a filter would be added to a rulset when enable was set torntrue, but nothing was done if enable was set to false.rnrnFix this by actually removing the filter via a new methodrnrulset_filters::remove_filter.rn
The asm_volatile_goto quirk is not needed anymore for 4.17, kernel has introduced a workaround macro __BPF_TRACING__.

Improve state switches (#1121)* Add way to dump scap_threadinfo w/ alternate bufsrnrnAdd a new scap_write_proclist_entry_bufs which takes a scap_threadinfornand a set of strings representing the various array-backed strings thatrncan be in a scap_threadinfo struct.rnrnIn the case of args/env/cgroups, which are represented within sinsp asrnvectors of strings, allow writing as an iovec, so the vector elementsrncan be written individually without having to be combined first.rnrnThis is useful when dumping the set of (sinsp) threads, as you can dumprna thread without copying all of the strings into the scap_threadinfornstruct.rnrn* Change thread_to_scap to do a shallow copyrnrnA big cost in creating a new capture file from a live event stream isrndumping the current set of threads to the capture file. This is donernin sinsp_thread_manager::dump_threads_to_file() and involves iteratingrnover the set of threads and converting each to a scap_threadinfornstruct, multiple times in fact.rnrnTo help make that more efficient, we can do a shallow copy of thernstrings from the sinsp_threadinfo struct given that the correspondingrnscap_threadinfo is temporary.rnrn{args,env,cgroups}_to_scap are replaced by {args,env,cgroups}_to_iovec,rnwhich assembles an iovec containing the strings in the various stringrnvectors, without actually copying anything in the common case. In therncase of truncation, a remainder string is used, which does get arntruncated copy of the last argument/env var/cgroup value that doesn'trnfit.rnrnAlso, there's now no need to allocate and populate a scap_threadinfornstruct when you're computing the write size for a thread. You can getrnall the sizes directly from the sinsp_threadinfo object.rn

Fix a bug in val_to_ring: large val_len (e.g. large read/write) were always casted to u16 so they generate a bogus value in val_to_ring, resulting in a corrupted event and potentially agent misbehavior since the snaplen would not be accurate anymore.

Fix a bug in val_to_ring: for some parameters, especially strings, the maximum length is not checked against the maximum 0xffff, so this can result in exporting junk to userspace, including non-terminated strings.
Fix snaplen bug: properly set the boundaries for the maximum snaplen, since the maximum length of a parameter due to the ring protocol and eBPF limitation is 0xffff.
Move away from BPF_MAP_TYPE_PERCPU_ARRAY for per-cpu maps and use a traditional BPF_MAP_TYPE_ARRAY so we can have a larger buffer area.
Remove an assert that would now trigger because I added a test that explicitly creates a large string parameter.

Introduce non-STL thread table API (#1142)* Store pointers, not objects, in thread maprnrn* New threadinfo map interfacernrnInstead of exposing the raw unordered map, we now explicitlyrnsupport only a few operations with a non-STL API.rnrnThe point is to enable swapping the underlying unordered_maprnwith a faster implementation.rn
Perf improvements to calculating the program hashUse a rolling hash to avoid doing repeated string copies andnlimit the hash to the first 1024 bytesn

Scap process blacklist (#1139)* libscap: add way to ignore all evts below a commrnrnAdd the ability to ignnore events for a process as well as all of itsrnchildren by comm. On fork/clone/exec, the comm return value is checkedrnand if the comm is found in a list of suppress comms, the tid is addedrnto a hash table of suppressed tids m_suppressed_tids.rnrnIn addition, on clone/fork/exec if the parent tid is in the suppressedrntid set the new tid is always added to the set as well.rnrnOn procexit the tid is always removed from the set of suppressedrntids. The procexit is only passed up if the thread was not previouslyrnsuppressed.rnrnIn scap_stats, include the number of suppresed threads. Will be usefulrnfor identifying runaway groups of suppressed threads in the face ofrndropped events and pid recycling, where you might end up with stale pidsrnin the suppressed tid set.rnrn* libsinsp: add ability to suppress events by commrnrnAdd the ability to suppress events by comm. sinsp::suppress_methods_commrnadds comms to the set. You can not specify more thanrnSCAP_MAX_SUPPRESSED_COMMS entries.rnrn* Sysdig: add ability to suppress events by commrnrnNew argument -U/--suppress-comm adds comm values to the inspector viarnsinsp::suppress_events_comm(). Skip proc scan in sinsp_dumper w/ threads_from_sinsp=true (#1164)The way sinsp_dumper::open() and ::fdopen() behaved was slightlyrninconsistent. fdopen() would unconditionally call scap_dump_open withrnskip_proc_scan=true, and open() would unconditionally callrnscap_dump_open with skip_proc_scan=false, regardless of the value ofrnthreads_from_sinsp.rnrnthreads_from_sinsp=true is a strong indicator that scap_dump_openrnshould *not* scan /proc for processes, as sinsp is going to write thernthreads list to the dump file immediately after opening.rnrnSo tie threads_from_sinsp to whether or not to skip the procrnscan--threads_from_sinsp=true implies skip_proc_scan.rnrnFor fdopen(), this is a change from unconditional to honoringrnthreads_from_sinsp. For open(), it requires adding a skip_proc_scanrnargument to scap_dump_open, setting it to false in other calls tornscap_dump_open outside of sinsp_dumper::open(), and tying it tornthreads_from_sinsp in sinsp_dumper::open().

Allow k8s filterchecks with analyzer (#1160)Allow k8s filterchecks when compiling with the analyzer. This matchesrnwhat we do for mesos--the filterchecks may not actually match events, asrnwe don't directly connect the inspector to external mesos/k8s servers,rnbut they will at least be defined.rnrnThis also ensures that a falco rules file validated with open sourcernfalco will also be validated by the sysdig agent.rnrnAs the analyzer does not have the necessary backing information for somernpreviously ifdef'd out filterchecks, when HAS_ANALYZER is definedrnreplace these with stubs that just return NULL/empty lists.

Complete ipv6 support (#1204)* Add new ipv6 typesrnrnAdd a new ipv6addr struct which contains the 16 bytes of the ip addressrnas 4 uint32_ts. It also has methods for comparisons and subnet checks.rnrnAlso add new PPM types PT_IPV6ADDR/PT_IPV6NET as well as a generalrnPT_IPADDR/PT_IPNET type. The general types will be used for things likernfilterchecks where they operate interchangeably on ipv4/ipv6 addresses.rnrn* Add ipv6 address support to sinsp interfacesrnrnFully support ipv6 addresses in sinsp_network_interfaces. When storingrnan ipv6 interface, use the new explicit type ipv6addr instead of 16-byternarrays. Also only save the network portion in a single ipv6 address.rnrnAdd methods import_ipv6_interface, is_ipv6addr_in_local_machine,rninfer_ipv6_address, which are used by update_fd to update sinsp_fdinfornstructs based on interface information.rnrn* Handle ipv6 addrs in comparisons/string conversionrnrnHandle PT_IPV6ADDR as a type in string conversions to/from rawvals, bothrndirectly and into the lua stack. Generally it's just inet_pton/inet_ntoprnon the bytes in the ipv6addr struct.rnrnAlso handle comparisons on PT_IPV6ADDR/PT_IPV6NET, using the equalityrnand netmast comparison operators on the struct.rnrnTo handle conversion/comparisons for PT_IPADDR/PT_IPNET, use the size ofrnthe rawval to determine if it's an ipv4 or ipv6 address and callrncomparison/converson method again with PT_IPV6ADDR/PT_IPV4ADDR asrnappropriate. For strings, infer the type based on whether the string hasrn'.' or ':' characters.rnrnThis required a change to the methods to take the paramrntype/format instead of a filtercheck_field_info, as there are other usesrnthat don't have a filtercheck_field_info.rnrn* Handle ipv6 addresses in csysdigrnrnIn get_thread_table_int, support SCAP_FD_IPV6 types, grabbing the rightrnpart of the sockinfo struct and doing the right conversion for thernaddress family.rnrnAdd a default column width for ipv6 addresses.rnrn* Support ipv6 addrs in fd.{*ip*,*net*} filterchecksrnrnChange all fd.ip/fd.net filterchecks to work on PT_IPADDR typesrninstead. When extracting, add tests for SCAP_FD_IPV6_* types and extractrnthe right part of the sockinfo struct.rnrnComparisons/conversion is already handled by the rawval_to_stringrnchanges that handle PT_IPADDR/PT_IPNET types.rnrn* Handle event parsing for ipv6 addressesrnrnInstead of simply handling ipv4 mapped ipv6 addresses, handle any ipv6rnaddress, filling in the right part of the sockinfo struct from the eventrnparameter.rnrnAlso handle source/dest swapping when determining the client/serverrnendpoints of a connection.rnrnConversions that used to work simply on an ipv6 address as byte arrayrnnow work on the m_b field of the ipv6addr struct.rnrn* Change typechar for server sockets to 4/6rnrnThe documentation of fd.typechar doesn't distinguish between serverrnsockets and non-server sockets, so simplify things by simply usingrn'4'/'6' to reflect the ipv4/ipv6 type.rnrn* Update chisels to support ipv6rnrnIn cases where a chisel's filter was specific to ipv4, also allow ipv6.rnrn* Don't return local strings from proto filterchecksrnrnThese were returning pointers to local string values on thernstack. Replace with m_tstr, a general purpose string in the object,rninstead.rn

Fix fd.net comparisons with in operator (#1252)When we added ipv6 support, we created a new param type PT_IPNET whichrnrepresents either an ipv4 netmask or ipv6 netmask, with the size beingrnused to determine the ultimate type.rnrnThat means we need to account for that type when using a CO_IN operatorrnand switch to checking each value in turn instead of doing a setrnmemberhip test.rnrnThis also means we need to call flt_compare with the correct argumentrnsizes so the size can be used to determine whether the netmask is ipv4rnor ipv6.

getsockopt() parser supportWhen getsockopt(SOL_SOCKET, SO_ERROR) is called, call the newnon_socket_status_changed callback to notify the analyzernabout the new socket state (OK/failed).nnThis is a new callback, as on_error doesn't really fit heren(it's not an error when the connection is successfullynestablished)n

Track socket errorsDistinguish between established, failed and pending connections.nnFailed means either a read/write error happened, or getsockopt(SOL_SOCKET,nSO_ERROR) returned an error.nnPending means the connect() was non-blocking and the actual connectionnstatus is still unknown.n

Fixed a compile issue when trying to make the project using VS2017 onu00e2u0080u00a6 (#1248)* Fixed a compile issue when trying to make the project using VS2017 on Win10 (x64).rnrn* Moved conditional includes to occur after system includes to keep system includes adjacent.rn

Lua parser interfaces (#1254)* Separate sinsp from lua parser apirnrnPreviously, the lua parser api was somewhat general purpose, with arnnotion of expressions linked together via operators and booleanrnexpressions. However, the expressions were always assumed to bernsinsp_filter_check objects and the filter was always assumed to be arnsinsp_filter object.rnrnWe may want to have other types of filters that still use the samernparsing, comparisons, and logical operators, but have different sourcesrnthan sinsp events. To make that easier, separate the lua parser api fromrnthe sinsp objects via intermediate classes, defined in gen_filter.{cpp,h}:rnrn - gen_event: a generalized event, used by the below classes. The onlyrn   property it has directly is an event timestamp. Also has the abilityrn   to set a check id which records the filter check id that matchedrn   this event. Everything else is implemented by subclasses.rnrn - gen_event_filter_factory: has virtual void methods to create a filterrn   and a filtercheck.rnrn - gen_event_filtercheck: represents a single filtering itemrn   e.g. proc.name in (curl, wget). Has variables to hold thern   comparison operator and logical operator and methods to parse thern   field name proc.name and add values curl, wget, etc.rnrn - gen_event_filter_expression: Allows nesting and combinations ofrn   gen_event_filtercheck objects.rnrn - gen_event_filter: represents a full filter expression as a chain ofrn   filterchecks put together. Has virtual void methods to addrn   filterchecks and push/pop expressions, as well as comparisons againstrn   gen_events.rnrnThe existing sinsp_event, sinsp_filter_check, etc. objects becomernchildren of these generic objects. Use curl_multi_wait()Don't call curl_multi_perform() in a busy wait loop, since it generates 1M+nsystem calls on a typical system where we have to wait 300-500ms for Dockernto send the response, leading to high CPU usage and saturation of kernelnbuffers. Instead, use curl_multi_wait() with infinite timeout, whichnreduces the system calls generated to a dozen.n

Handle mmap failure gracefully (#1324)For some reason, scap uses MAP_FAILED as a sentinel to indicate the absencernof the buffer, whereas in the BPF code I was mostly using NULL. So, in thernrare cases where mmap fails, this can cause a segfault while scap_closerncleans up structures.rnrnIt would be cleaner to just move all the code to use NULL, but since arnlarge portion of the kmod-related scap functions rely on the MAP_FAILED,rnit's safer to just adapt the BPF part to use MAP_FAILED as well.rnrnAs part of the fix, make sure we don't leak any fds when mmap fails.

Fix potential memory leak in libelfSome old versions of libelf (such as the one used in CentOS 6) are prone tonmemory leaks when elf_strptr() is called, under some circumstances thenmemory is not freed even upon correct invocation of elf_end().nnEventually we should ship our own updated version of libelf, but sincenpeople are currently welcome to build without using our bundledndependencies, it's worth fixing anyway.nnThe fix consists in opening the file via mmap rather than reading it vianallocated buffers, which is something I honestly thought libelf was alreadyndoing by default, so it was my intention to begin with.nnThe fix went upstream in:nn```n2016-08-07  Mark Wielaard  <mjw@redhat.com>nnt* elf_compress.c (__libelf_reset_rawdata): Check scn->flags andntfree rawdata_base when malloced. Set ELF_F_MALLOCED for scn->flags.nt* elf_end.c (elf_end): Check scn->flags and free rawdata_base ifntmalloced.nt* libelfP.h (struct Elf_Scn): Document flags ELF_F_MALLOCED usage.n```nnvalgrind memory leak:nn```n==44437== 213,655 bytes in 2 blocks are definitely lost in loss record 3 of 3n==44437==at 0x483577F: malloc (vg_replace_malloc.c:299)n==44437==by 0x403812: __libelf_set_rawdata_wrlock (elf_getdata.c:262)n==44437==by 0x40355E: elf_strptr (elf_strptr.c:128)n```n

Thisrnis in m_pevt_storage, NULL by default but if non-NULL will bernfreed. This will be used to pass container events to the inspector viarnthe queue.rnrn* Add tid for container events, pass to inspectorrnrnMake sure container_json events have a real thread id by passing it asrnan argument to container_to_sinsp_event.rnrnModify notify_new_container to use the non-blocking queue to pass eventsrnto the inspector instead of m_meta_evt.rnrn* Add all info to parsing/dumping of json eventsrnrnPreviously, CONTAINER_JSON events had some, but not all, of the infornthat was in a sinsp_container_info object. Fix this so all importantrninfo is both dumped to json in container_to_json and parsed inrnparse_container_json_evt.rnrn* Refactor docker info fetches to be asyncrnrnRefactor docker metadata fetches to be asynchronous, using the frameworkrnin sysdig::async_key_value_source.rnrndocker_async_source (a global static so it can be long-lived) is nowrnresponsible for looking up docker metadata. Some methods that used to bernin docker:: like parse_docker(), get_docker(), etc move torndocker_async_source. It dequeues requests, calling parse_docker() tornlook up the information as needed, and calls store_value() to pass thernmetadata back to the caller.rnrndocker::resolve now uses parse_docker_async to schedule the lookup withrndocker_async_source. Before scheduling the lookup it creates a stubrncontainer with type UNKNOWN (UNKNOWN because you can't tell therndifference between cri and docker containers only from the cgroup), withrnthe id set, and with a name/image set to incomplete. This ensures thatrnthreads have some associated container info object with it. In therncallback once the full metadata is available, it callsrnnotify_new_container, which creates the CONTAINER_JSON event and pushesrnit to the inspector.rnrnThere's a fair amount of bookeeping to make sure that the containerrnmetadata has a valid tid. The very first tid that creates the containerrnoften exits after forking of the real container entrypoint, so you needrnto keep track of the top tid in the container for every call torndocker::resolve() and replace it if you find it's exited.rnrnPreviously, on the first error fetching container metadata, a flagrnm_enabled would be set to false, and all subsequent attempts to fetchrncontainer metadata would be skipped. Now that lookups are done in thernbackground, I think it makes sense to always try a lookup for everyrncontainer, even after failures. So remove m_enabled entirely from therndocker engine.rnrnAlso, as a part of this change, reorganize the way the async lookups arerndone to better support the choices of different osen (linux, windows,rnand HAS_CAPTURE). Instead of compiling out the curl handles whenrnHAS_CAPTURE is false, always compile the code for them but don't evenrnattempt any lookups in docker::resolve. Note thatrndocker_async_source::get_docker no longer changes behavior based onrnHAS_CAPTURE.rnrn* Fix cri::resolve to work w UNKNOWN container infosrnrncri::resolve might be called after docker::resolve, so there could be arncontainer_info object with type == UNKNOWN.rnrnUpdate it to handle this i.e. do the lookup anyway.rnrn* Use tbb, libcurl on osx, disable libidn2rnrnWe need it now that tbb is a core part of the inspector and that therncurl part of the docker container engine isn't #ifdefd with HAS_CAPTURE.rnrnBoth are already downloaded/built as dependencies of sysdig so it's justrna matter of CMakeLists.txt config.rnrnAlso, disable libidn2 explicitly when building libcurl. On OSX buildsrnthis gets picked up from an autodetected library, while it does not getrnpicked up on linux. We already disable libidn1, so also disable libidn2.rnrn* Serialize/unserialize is_pod_sandboxrnrnInstead of inferring is_pod_sandbox from the container name only forrndocker, save/load it to json directly from the container info. Thisrnensures it works for other container engines than docker.rnrn* Get rid of CT_UNKNOWNrnrnInstead of having a CT_UNKNOWN type, iniitally set the type to CT_DOCKERrnwhen starting the async lookup. Cri runs next and if the grpc lookuprncompletes successfully this will be replaced with CT_CRIO. If both grpcrnand docker metadata lookups fail the type will remain at CT_DOCKER.rnrn* Just include sinsp classrnrnIt's a bit simpler than including sinsp.h, which has many many dependentrnheader files.rnrn* Add note on why the container evt needs a tidrnrnIt's required for the container.* filterchecks to work.rnrn* Only start async lookup thread if docker foundrnrnCall detect_docker, which identifies a docker container, before startingrnthe async lookup thread. If no docker containers are ever used, thernasync thread won't be started.rnrn* Use a static for the string incompleternrn* Fix typo CRI -> dockerrnrn* Set all container metadata fields to incompleternrnInstead of just setting the image to incomplete, set all containerrnmetadata fields to incomplete.rnrn* Don't protect m_metadata_deadline w HAS_ANALYZERrnrnIt's filled in when using the analyzer, but we can define it in bothrncases and just not use it when there is no analyzer.rn

Performance improvements of ring buffer processingWorking on a feature that's particularly sensitive to event drops andntruncated snaplens, I did some performance experiments.nnMy chosen workload is a sustained busy loop that does nothing more thannwriting 10KB at a time to /dev/null using `write()`. On my laptop, on ansingle core I have a throughput of ~1.5M evt/s. Since I am explicitlynrunning with a very high snaplen (65k), this workload would generate ansustained 7 GB/s (!) on a single core inside a ring buffer that could keepnup with the consumption. Since our buffer is 8MB, this means that userspacenhas ~1ms to process all the data inside a ring buffer, before starting tondrop. This workload highlighted some potential low hanging fruits that I'llndescribe here.nnTo start, this is how the whole thing behaves today, using eBPF (kmod isnsimilar, but with less overhead):nnTotal events (including dropped): 11.3MnDropped events: 10.6MnnPretty bad, we dropped 95% of the events.nnUsing an off-time CPU analysis methodology this is what I get during a 10snrun:nn$ sudo cpudist -O -m -P -p $(pgrep sysdig) 10 1nTracing off-CPU time... Hit Ctrl-C to end.nnpid = 27973 sysdignn msecs   : count distributionn 0 -> 1  : 16   |**  |n 2 -> 3  : 0||n 4 -> 7  : 0||n 8 -> 15 : 0||n16 -> 31 : 315  |****************************************|n32 -> 63 : 1||nn$ sudo offcputime -p $(pgrep sysdig) 10nTracing off-CPU time (us) of PID 31663 by user + kernel stack for 10 secs.nnfinish_task_switchn__schedulenschedulenexit_to_usermode_loopnprepare_exit_to_usermodenswapgs_restore_regs_and_return_to_usermodenscap_nextn-sysdig (31663)n50nnfinish_task_switchn__schedulenschedulendo_nanosleepnhrtimer_nanosleepnsys_nanosleepndo_syscall_64nentry_SYSCALL_64_after_hwframen__GI___nanosleepn-sysdig (31663)n9824891nnSo, while sysdig was dropping buffers like crazy, it was also leisurelynspending the vast majority of its time off CPU (315 * 30ms ~= 9.8s), as anresult of the 30ms sleep we use when we find the buffer empty. This happensnbecause the userspace consumer is not CPU-bound, so it's able to keep upnwith the producer, and when it catches up it goes to sleep, and during thenpause time the producer sends 100s MB of data, overflowing the buffer.nnThe general approach here is to obviously enlarge the buffer and/orndiminish the sleeping time. Diminishing the sleeping time is tricky becausenit increases CPU utilization, and increasing the ring buffer is trickynbecause it's a lot of kernel memory wasted on multi core. To absorb a 30msnpause at 7 GB/s the per-core buffer needs to be 200+MB large.nnThese are the things I experimented with:nn- I replaced the fixed 30ms sleep with a simple adaptive algorithm: everyn  time we find the buffer to be empty, we simply double the time we willn  sleep until we reach a ceiling (30ms). If the buffer is not empty, wen  reset the sleep threshold so we will start polling more aggressively nextn  time (500us in this PR).nn- I removed the logic of max consecutive wait, since I couldn't find an  sense to it: regardless of whether we wait or not, at the end of eachn  period we always refill the buffer and make it available to the caller,n  so it's not that multiple consecutive waits can cause any harm (that In  can see, at least), hence they don't need to be tracked.nn- The tail of the buffer was previously advanced when the buffers aren  refilled, which for any buffer it could potentially be several us/msn  after it is consumed since we have to wait for all the buffers to ben  emptied by userspace, thus keeping the ring buffer needlessly occupied.n  The tail is now advanced every time we are done completely consuming an  buffer. The number of operations should be exactly the same. Admittedlyn  this is a micro optimization, more for readability of the code, so thatn  `check_scap_next_wait` always looks at the new amount of data available,n  rather than counting the already consumed one, which I found odd.nnWhile this doesn't solve a bursty workload, it does wonders for a sustainednworkload, as we can see here after the patch for the same stress test:nnTotal events (including dropped): 8MnDropped events: 60knnNot bad at all for a 8MB ring buffer, < 1% dropped (the lower throughput isnbecause now the kernel probe is spending much more time copying all thosen10KB into the ring buffer, since it's finding it free).nnAnd the CPU of sysdig remains pretty much the same. In particular, duringnidle time, the adaptive sleep will always quickly reach the ceiling andnstay there (see the relatively minor amount of sleeps under 30ms for then10s period):nn$ sudo cpudist -O -m -P -p $(pgrep sysdig) 10 1nTracing off-CPU time... Hit Ctrl-C to end.nnpid = 28645 sysdignn msecs   : count distributionn 0 -> 1  : 37   |****|n 2 -> 3  : 11   |*   |n 4 -> 7  : 11   |*   |n 8 -> 15 : 11   |*   |n16 -> 31 : 317  |****************************************|nnWhen we are under sustained workload, the adaptive sleep will alwaysninstead be at the floor, allowing us to be very responsive to the sustainednload:nn$ sudo cpudist -O -m -P -p $(pgrep sysdig) 10 1nTracing off-CPU time... Hit Ctrl-C to end.nnpid = 28645 sysdignn msecs   : count distributionn 0 -> 1  : 12746|****************************************|n 2 -> 3  : 0||n 4 -> 7  : 1||nnThis is rather simple but seems to be doing the job. Ideally I'd like tonreplace it with a better feedback loop, where the current throughput of thenring buffer is estimated (via timestamps and amounts read over a movingnaverage), and the polling interval is calculated based on that. This way,nit would be even more robust with bursty workloads.nnAlso, a reader might ask why we don't move to a proper I/O multiplexednmodel using poll(). Unfortunately, it's not obvious that it would helpnperformance, in the past I've done experiments on this and the overheadnnecessary on the kernel side to maintain the state and wake up the consumernwasn't acceptable even with generous overflow thresholds when you talknabout millions of events per second. It's possible that the tests weren'tnthorough, but that's certainly a much more significant work.n

Don't enqueue an async request when there's one already activeIf an async lookup is in progress, the lookup key is already removednfrom m_request_set but it's still present in m_value_map, so a subsequentncall to lookup() with the same key will do the same lookup again.nnAlso, when the request had a callback set, upon success we will removenthe value from m_value_map, _including the callback_, so the duplicatenlookup will store the result in m_value_map without calling the callbacknagain.nnThis patch ensures that there's always at most one in flight requestnfor a particular key.n
