Add `async_key_value_source::get_complete_results()`Sometimes there's no good place to call `lookup()` again on the asyncndata source -- e.g. the container detection engine may never be callednagain for a particular container (if the only process in that containernnever calls `execve()` or `chroot()` or `clone()`).nnThe best solution in that case is to supply a callback to be rannfrom the async lookup, but that introduces thread safety issuesnto the involved data.nn`get_complete_results()` allows batch processing of lookup resultsnin the main thread.n

Allow delayed async_key_value_source lookupsThis patch adds `async_key_value_source::lookup_delayed()`, which worksnthe same as `lookup()`, but instead of dispatching the request immediately,nit starts processing it after a specified delay.nnNotable implementation changes:n* instead of a simple list, we now use a priority queue of tasks, orderedn  by scheduled timen* we need to switch to a timed wait in `run()`, as we have to end the waitn  whenever the time comes to start a previously scheduled requestnnNote: due to a gcc bug, we need to explicitly handle infinite timeout,ninstead doing a timed wait until `time_point::max()`, see:nhttps://stackoverflow.com/questions/39041450/stdcondition-variable-wait-until-surprising-behaviourn
Mark the async_key_value_source constructor noexceptIt cannot throw an exception anyway and this calms down code inspectionnwhen creating a static instancen

Raise the iov limit in eBPFWhile playing with HTTP/2, I noticed gRPC tends to make heavy use ofnvectorized I/O with sendmsg()/recvmsg(). Basically every single requestntranslates into many HTTP/2 frames, and gRPC seems to like sending each onenof them as a separate element of the vector and then batch all of them intona single system call. So, it's pretty normal to see requests that reachnnumbers as high as 32 (possibly even higher, I haven't encountered themnyet). Since each element of the vector is very small (e.g. 9 bytes HTTP/2nheader), with the current limit of 8 it's easy to reach a situation wherenwe get truncated data even if the snaplen is set to a higher number,nbecause we just collect the first 8 elements of the vector.nnThe limit of 8 was initially (empirically) set by me because it was thenonly way to make old kernels (4.12-4.13) accept those programs and not runninto a state explosion. Since we now support just 4.14.0+, 32 should be anmore decent limit, and I confirm it doesn't break 4.14.0, which is thenversion with the oldest (aka stringent) verifier we support.n

Start tracking k8s liveness probes (#1320)* Remove unneeded class forward declarationrnrnNot used in this header file, so shouldn't be needed.rnrn* Start tracking k8s liveness/readiness probesrnrnK8s has a similar but not identical method as docker for containerrnhealth checks. They are called liveness/readiness probes and are a partrnof the pod specification, and not a part of the image.rnrnLuckily, the pod configuration *is* a part of the container metadata asrnstringified json, with a labelrnannotation.kubectl.kubernetes.io/last-applied-configuration, so we canrnuse that label to identify liveness/readiness probes.rnrnNew methods in the docker container resolver handle parsing the podrnspecification (and healthcheck info) out of the container json andrncreating health probes from them.rnrnA new class sinsp_container_info::container_health_probe represents onernof these health probes. It has a proberntype (healthcheck/liveness/readiness), the executable and arguments, andrnmethods to serialize/unserialize from json. The serialization doesn'trnpreserve the original container json--they only keep the exe + args.rnrnThe container info now has a list of possible health probe objects andrniterates over them when dumping the container to json.rnrnFor threads, switch everything to use a threadinfo category instead of arnsimple bool for has healthcheck. The possible values for the categoryrnare:rnrn  - CAT_NONE: no specific categoryrn  - CAT_CONTAINER: a process run in a container and *not* anyrnof the following more specific categories.rn  - CAT_HEALTHCHECK: part of a container healthcheckrn  - CAT_LIVENESS_PROBE: part of a k8s liveness probern  - CAT_READINESS_PROBE: part of a k8s readiness probernrnIdentify_healthcheck becomes identify_category() butrnotherwise behaves the same (passing categories down and checking thernargs list otherwise).rnrnThe logic in indentify_healthcheck tries to handle the common casesrnfirst:rnrn - not running in a container or container info not present: CAT_NONErn - vpid=1: CAT_CONTAINERrn - inherit categories other than CAT_NONE directly from parentrnrnIf those fail, the more expensive steps of matching against the healthrncheck args and possibly traversing the parent state are done.rnrnThe filterchecks aren't quite as generic as the threadinfo categories tornkeep the filtering simple. A new fieldrnproc.is_container_{liveness,readiness}_probe checks for k8srnliveness/readiness probes, and container.{liveness,readiness}_probernprints the exe + args.rn

More flexible way to build bpf probe in-container (#1443)* More flexible way to build bpf probe in-containerrnrnThere are some cases where a user wants to use the BPF probe and runrnsysdig/falco/agent/etc from a container, but doesn't want to installrnkernel headers/sources on the host. We already had two versions ofrnthis--minikube and cos. Each had nearly identical steps of downloadingrnthe kernel sources, applying the running config, and building the ebpfrnprogram using the kernel sources as a basis.rnrnThis refactors the minikube/cos steps to share common steps, as well asrnallowing for a more generic path that downloads the kernel sourcesrnin-container. To use it, set the environment variablernBPF_USE_LOCAL_KERNEL_SOURCES to any value. In a docker run command, itrnwould be set via:rnrndocker run ... -e BPF_USE_LOCAL_KERNEL_SOURCES=1 ... sysdig/sysdigrnrnI tested this with a locally built sysdig container and the following:rnrn1. Minikube version v0.33.1: uname -a=Linux minikube 4.15.0 #1 SMP Fri Jan 18 22:39:33 UTC 2019 x86_64 GNU/Linuxrn2. COS Container-Optimized OS 69-10895.273.0 stable: uname -a=Linux mstemm-sysdig-testing-2 4.14.124+ #1 SMP Fri Jun 14 22:50:58 PDT 2019 x86_64 Intel(R) Xeon(R) CPU @ 2.30GHz GenuineIntel GNU/Linuxrn3. Amazon linux 2: uname -a=Linux ip-172-31-48-89.ec2.internal 4.14.123-111.109.amzn2.x86_64 #1 SMP Mon Jun 10 19:37:57 UTC 2019 x86_64 x86_64 x86_64 GNU/LinuxrnrnFor #1/#2, the docker run command line was: docker run -it --privileged --net=host -v /var/run/docker.sock:/host/var/run/docker.sock -v /dev:/host/dev -v /proc:/host/proc:ro -v /boot:/host/boot:ro -v /lib/modules:/host/lib/modules:ro -v /usr:/host/usr:ro -v /etc:/host/etc:ro -e SYSDIG_BPF_PROBE= ...rnrnFor #3, added -e BPF_USE_LOCAL_KERNEL_SOURCES=1.rnrnAll 3 could build the ebpf program. #1 and #3 had this error during thernkernel config steps, but it's not a regression and didn't interfere withrnbuilding the ebpf program:rnrnscripts/extract-cert.c:21:25: fatal error: openssl/bio.h: No such file or directoryrncompilation terminated.rnrn* Add SYSDIG_ prefix to BPF_USE_LOCAL_KERNEL_SOURCESrnrnConvention that external env vars start with SYSDIG_.rn

Get CRI resource limits from cgroupsIf the CRI runtime is _not_ containerd, we need to find the resourcenlimit values ourselves directly from cgroups. However, we cannotndo this synchronously in `cri::resolve()`, because at this pointnthe values may not yet be set completely. Instead, we delay the cgroupnlookup by one second.nnNote: we do try to get the limits synchronously as well and if wen  succeed for all the values we expect (memory limit, cpu shares,n  cpu quota and period), we don't do the second delayed lookup.nnNote: success is defined as having values both larger than zeron  and smaller than an arbitrary too large value (4 TiB, to avoidn  overflow when converting to a 32-bit number of kilobytes)nnNote: It seems that CRI-o sets up cgroup *limits* only when *requests*n  are set as well, so we want at least a message in this case.n

Track container lookup progress in a separate mapThis is to avoid the following scenario:n1. Async Docker lookup startsn   - container state is now incomplete Docker lookupn2. Sync CRI lookup startsn3. While the CRI lookup is running, Docker lookup failsn  - container state is now failed Docker lookupn4. Sync CRI lookup failsn   - container state is now failed CRI lookupn4. Docker lookup is triggered again for the same containern   (we no longer have any record that we've already triedn   and failed to talk to Docker)n

Add set operator intersects (#1501)* Add set matching operator INTERSECTSrnrnFor some kinds of filterchecks (notably, json_event filterchecks inrnfalco), a filtercheck can extract not a single value but a set ofrnvalues. An example of this is extracting the privileged flag from allrncontainers specified in a k8s audit event.rnrnIn these cases, it's desirable to support a set intersection operatorrnthat compares the extracted values from the event and the values on thernrhs of the operator. It differs from CO_IN because (a,b,c) in (a,b) isrnfalse while (a,b,c) intersects (a,b) is true.rnrnSo define a has operator CO_INTERSECTS and support it when parsing filterrnexpressions so they can be used by falco.rnrnINTERSECTS is implemented as a valid comparison for syscall events, butrnsince there can only be a single extracted value, INTERSECTS is reallyrnthe same as IS.rnrn* Add path_prefix_{match,search} use w/ stringsrnrnThe existing uses of path_prefix_{match,search} rely on pointers tornstorage not owned by the object. This makes sense for syscall eventsrnwhere the data is ultimately in the ring buffer.rnrnThere are other uses where it's desirable to use normal strings, so addrna method that copies the string into the object and uses a pointer tornthat string.rn

Allow maintaining lookup state per container engineThis matters for async-capable engines, where each of them needsnto know if a lookup for that particular engine is in progress.nnWith just the stub entry in container_manager's map, we can onlynkeep track of a single engine's background lookup, which causesnproblems for Docker+CRI containers (CRI will be async again soon,nhopefully).n

Remove stub container objectsSince the only purpose of the stub container objects was to keepntrack of an async lookup happening in the background, removenthem and use m_lookup_state instead.nnThis introduces a behavior change in Docker and CRI (the only twonengines which connect to a daemon to fetch container metadata):nwe no longer call add_container() when the lookup is started,nbut instead we generate a container JSON event even when the daemonnrequest fails. Since this means we can receive multiple JSON eventsnfor a single container, we enable extra filtering logic in thenparser for those events:n- we ignore all events for which we already have a complete containern  stored in container_manager. This means that after the firstn  successful lookup, all subsequent ones are ignored (in practice,n  only a single lookup will be successful, but e.g. calling out ton  Docker and its containerd CRI socket separately might actuallyn  succeed twice)n- for failed lookups (before the first successful one), we don'tn  add the container to the manager's map, but still call then  on_new_container callbacks.nnThe resulting semantics of JSON events/callbacks is:n- JSON events are delivered at most once (when the first successfuln  lookup finishes)n- callbacks are called at least once (once for every failed lookupn  and once for the final successful one, if any)n

Always reset cont. events when reading from scaps (#1513)I noticed a regression where a recently built sysdig would not readrncontainer information in .scap files. In this case, the capture file hasrntwo initial PPME_CONTAINER_JSON_E events: One with a container eventrnwith incomplete information, and one with final container event information:rnrn```rn10-04 00:01:34.230950 Parsing ContainerrnJSON={container:{Mounts:[],cpu_period:100000,cpu_quota:0,cpu_shares:1024,env:[],id:697956520d89,image:incomplete,imagedigest:incomplete,imageid:incomplete,imagerepo:incomplete,imagetag:incomplete,ip:0.0.0.0,is_pod_sandbox:false,labels:null,memory_limit:0,metadata_deadline:0,name:incomplete,port_mappings:[],privileged:false,swap_limit:0,type:0}}rnrn10-04 00:01:34.231016 Parsing ContainerrnJSON={container:{Mounts:[],cpu_period:100000,cpu_quota:0,cpu_shares:1024,env:[],id:697956520d89,image:nginx,imagedigest:sha256:96fb261b66270b900ea5a2c17a26abbfabe95506e73c3a3c65869a6dbe83223a,imageid:f68d6e55e06520f152403e6d96d0de5c9790a89b4cfc99f4626f68146fa1dbdc,imagerepo:nginx,imagetag:latest,ip:172.17.0.2,is_pod_sandbox:false,labels:{maintainer:NGINXrnDocker Maintainers <docker-maint@nginx.com>},memory_limit:0,metadata_deadline:0,name:hopeful_taussig,port_mappings:[],privileged:false,swap_limit:0,type:0}rn```rnrnWhen deciding whether or not to actually parse a container jsonrnevent (sinsp_parser::parse_container_json_evt), the method relies onrnevt->m_tinfo_ref being non-null. Normally, that is reset inrnsinsp_parser::reset(), but there's an exception for container events,rnwhich in the case of a live capture are created by the containerrnresolvers and pushed to the inspector over a queue.rnrnHowever, for container events read from capture files, they come fromrnthe capture file and re-use a single sinsp_event object associated withrnthe inspector. In this case, the threadinfo *must* be reset.rnrnThe fix is to qualify how container events are reset to always resetrnthem when they are read from capture files.

[SMAGENT-2066] Control driver printing when in interrupt context (#1522)A customer reported an issue where the driver would deadlock the systemrnby attempting to printk() while the schedule lock is already held due torna context switch. This occurred because the context switch triggered arndeferred drop_x event, which prints a log message when it's processed.rnPrinting the log message caused the framebuffer helper in the consolernprint driver to attempt a context switch and hang the system on thernschedule lock.rnrnThis is a rare event, as it requires the kernel console log level to bernset to ERROR or above and for a print to occur while processing arncontext switch tracepoint.

Partial liveness/readiness k8s probe parsing (#1523)* Get {live,readi}ness probes from relatd containersrnrnAdd the ability to fetch liveness/readiness probe information fromrnrelated containers when not available in the container info labels.rnrnWhen starting k8s deployments, a pod contains a long-lived pauserncontainer and shorter-lived containers that are restarted as therncontainer process exits, is restarted, etc. Only the pause container hasrnthe necessary ..../last-applied-configuration label that contains thernpod's liveness/readiness probes. The shorter-lived container does have arnreference to the pause container, though, via a io.kubernetes.sandbox.idrnlabel.rnrnSo when the container doesn't have a .../last-applied-configurationrnlabel, see if it has a io.kubernetes.sandbox.id label, try to look uprnthat container, and if it has liveness/readiness probes, copy the probesrnfrom that container.rnrnAs the container lookup occurs in the async lookup thread, this PRrnshould *not be merged* until some other container info changes to addrnadditional thread-safety are made.rnrn* Use sinsp_container_manager::entry_ptr_trnrnAllows for later changes of the type to something like a shared_ptr.rnrn* Fix compile errorsrnrn* Use SINSP_DEBUGrn

Fix crash when `scap_get_threadlist` is called before the first actual eventThe last synthetic event is actually m_evt (the real event from the driver)nso if we call scap_get_threadlist (and process the resulting syntheticnevents) before a real event happens, m_evt is still uninitialized.nnThis is pretty hard to hit as we explicitly skip the first time whennthe function should be called (`if (m_next_flush_time_ns != 0)`),nso it happens only when the setup (/proc scan, container detection)ntakes long enough and/or the stars align just right.nnRemoving the check and getting the thread list even the first timenaround crashes sysdig reliably and this patch fixes it.nnThe patch basically stops scheduling the actual event as a syntheticnevent (we don't read data from the driver for synthetic eventsnso if it's the first event ever, it contains bogus data).n

Catch polymorphic exceptions polymorphically (#1533)* Catch polymorphic exceptions polymorphicallyrnrnThere are a couple of places in the sysdig code base that catchrn`sinsp_exception` by value instead of by reference.  `sinsp_exception`rnis a polymorphic type with known subclasses.  If an instance of arnsubtype is thrown, then caught by value as an `sinsp_exception`, badrnthings (tm) can happen.rnrnThis update changes all catches to catch by const reference.  It alsornchanges places that rethrow a caught exception to do it the right way.rnrnFinally, I pull `sinsp_exception` andrn`sinsp_capture_interrupt_exception` out of `sinsp.h` and into their ownrnheaders so client code can use them without pulling in all of `sinsp.h`.rnrn* Add `scap_open_exception`rnrnAt some point, `sinsp_exception` was modified to support a cornerrncase where the engineer wanted to communicate an error status fromrna specific API.  Rather than build that into `sinsp_exception`,rnwhere we use that use case exactly twice across the entire system,rnthis change factors that corner case out into a separate subclassrnof `sinsp_exception`.rn
